😂🤷🏻‍♀️Happy Tuesday 🤗

Tell me something about yourself! I’ll go first:

I had a joke radio show in college. It was called, “My Names Emily and I Like Jokes” (I’m very literal what can I say 😂)

The first National Park I went to on a solo trip (so outside of Colorado parks that I did solo day trips to) was actually the Petrified Forest! I was on my way to the Grand Canyon and thought why not. I had no dreams or plans of visiting all the parks at that time. Like at all 😂 

Things change :)

It’s been a busy few months. To say the least. 💜 #schmidtspartner 

I’m so grateful for all the opportunities to travel I’ve had, but I’d be lying if I said it was never stressful. Packing for different locations and climates with little time at home in between can be exhausting. So I try to routinize the process as much as I can. 

Pack only the things that I truly love and know that work for me. 

Like @schmidtsnaturals deodorant. There’s always some in my home and in my luggage. I love that Schmidt’s is committed to natural protection — never using artificial fragrances, parabens, baking soda or aluminum salts. It’s perfect for my sensitive skin and gives me the 24-hour protection that I need. 

It’s one less thing to worry about. So I can spend less time packing, and more time enjoying the views 🤗

This time of year always leads to self-reflection. For me anyways. The holidays and my birthday are all within a month of each other. These goalposts of sorts. An easy way to reflect on “this time last year”.

I try to notice accomplishments and goals met, but also the other side. Things that didn’t go as planned. What I wish or thought I might do and didn’t. 

And reminding myself that it’s never too late — to “make it”. Not in the sense that at any time I’ve actually made “it” but in creativity. The things I literally want to make.

Physical and mental and relational. It’s never too late to make those things or change things in life. Creativity only grows with time and space. 

And I can’t help but be grateful for what’s behind as I’m looking forward to what’s ahead. ✨

Happy Thanksgiving ✨💜

Day 24: I’m thankful for this space. Truly. I never thought taking photos and writing long captions would bring me what it has. 

A community of people who are incredibly supportive and encouraging. I know I can’t always respond to everyone, but I’m amazed every day by how generous you are with me.

Opportunities to work with brands that I love and actually be paid for my creative work. Something I always dreamed of but didn’t think was practical for someone to pivot to at my age.

An outlet that has helped me to process emotions and thoughts in a way that can be hard otherwise. Somehow an audience of thousands really can be easier than one. 

And a reminder every day that despite all the noise there is real goodness and love all around. It’s here.

Thank you 💜

Hope you have the best day available. What are you thankful for?

Alone but not lonely 💜

I write about this a lot. Because I’m asked about it a lot. And it seems like this time of year is when feelings of loneliness tend to increase. 

And the truth is, like I’ve said before, I really don’t feel lonely solo traveling or being alone. I can’t even really remember the last time I did. And it’s not because I’m any different or enlightened or maybe naive or simple. 

It’s just because I’ve learned over the last almost 37 years to like my own company. If loneliness is a lack of connection, then I don’t have anything to worry about — because I’m connected to myself. To nature. My surroundings. 

I heard someone say once that loneliness is a feeling of weakness when you’re alone while solitude is a feeling of strength. And I feel the difference. I feel the strength. In me. 

No matter where I am. I’m never truly alone.

I just got back from visiting family in Illinois. I grew up for much of my life near the Illinois and Iowa border. And I have to admit, as a teen I couldn’t imagine why anyone would choose to live there. 

So I left and moved to Louisiana. Then Colorado. As the years have passed and I’ve spent more time exploring, Ive of course — as seems to always happen with time — learned to love and appreciate it. There’s really nothing like a Midwest sunset. 

So I was so happy to find this rental in Iowa. Down the kind of country road that I’m used to. Outside a small town and in between corn fields. 

When I walked into the cabin I felt warmth. Physically and viscerally. When I walked into the conservatory I felt awe. And it was perfect.

This @airbnb is in Winterset Iowa — the birthplace of John Wayne and inspiration behind the Bridges of Madison County. It’s also a venue for weddings etc so message the hosts first to see if there will be any events in the space before booking :) 

Have you visited Iowa? What place has been surprising to you?

I can’t believe it’s December already. I probably say this every year. What’s that saying, “the days are long but the years are short”? I’m reminded of it most this time of year. 

And despite my best efforts, during this time I can start to feel like I still need to “fit it all in”. I need to accomplish the goals I set for the year. Finish strong. Reorganize my entire life and set myself up for success before I enter into another year of my life and then another year on the calendar. 

And while there’s obviously nothing wrong with accomplishing goals or reflecting on where you’d like to be — I’m also reminded that suffering comes from wishing things were different. And that I can continue to work on my goals and plans without wishing I was in a different space than I am. 

I can be present for whatever this month brings without wishing it away or holding myself to unrealistic expectations. 

So I think I’m going to do that. ✨

Do everything like it’s the last time. I’ve been thinking about that phrase. Someone close to me said it recently after being diagnosed with an incurable illness. 

And while, obviously, at first it seems like maybe a morbid thought to ruminate on — I really don’t see it that way. I’m just reminded to focus on the now. The present that is a present. 

Instagram has helped me with this over the years, to be honest. When I started posting more I started looking for beauty in a different way. My focus was on uncovering and sharing rather than letting it pass me by. 

And I’m grateful for that. For the opportunity to find beauty in all things. To lean in to whimsy and fun whenever I can. Make each moment special. 

Because they are.

And I’m not going to disappoint her. 

Happy Saturday 💜

🍩 and ☕️ with a view ✨

Did you know you can eat fresh, warm donuts at 14,115 ft on the summit of Pikes Peak?? You can hike, drive or — my personal favorite — ride the Pikes Peak Cog Railway up the mountain. The railway is one of my favorite things to do during the winter months. 

One of the last remaining cog railways in the United States, it’s recently been refurbished completely and takes visitors from the station in Manitou Springs to the newly renovated and reopened summit visitor center. 

There you can enjoy the world famous donuts made fresh daily. The recipe is top secret and optimized for the extreme elevation — they would collapse at a lower elevation and have to be enjoyed at the summit. 

It’s something I always recommend and love to repeat ✨

I used to think I was boring. Hopelessly average. That I’d never have interesting stories to tell. Never be the person someone would look to advice on anything other than maybe teaching math. Sometimes I still have a fleeting thought like those.

But I reject it pretty quickly. Whether it’s getting older, traveling and spending time alone, or just working on my confidence — I know I have something to offer. That we all do. I feel driven to share my stories. 

Not because I think they’re better or more interesting, but because I know that they’re not. We all have an interesting story to tell. We are all unique. We all have experiences that no one else has. But it’s the feelings that resonate with us all. 

We learn from stories when they make us feel something — whether they’re average or compelling circumstances. And that is exactly why we should share them freely — not just in one area of our lives. Because someone needs to hear it. Someone is waiting for your story. Share it with them. 💜

‘Tis the season ✨

Getting my holiday cards ready to send out this week. One of my favorite parts of the season. As a kid I remember looking forward to all of the cards and letters our family received. It was always so fun to see what people had been up to and how they chose to present themselves. 

When I started teaching I would make a card of classroom photos to give to each of my classes. But I didn’t think I could send my own card without the traditional family or kids. 

So I started sending cards with pictures of my cats and maybe I made an appearance with them. Then one year I remember seeing a lot of things written about “single” or “lonely girl” Christmas cards. In jest, photos with single women crying or with bottles of wine or a fake family. And they’re funny, sure. 

But I had this very strong reaction of “But that’s not my reality”. I’m having a great time and doing lots of cool things and who says I can’t send my own card? With just pictures of myself? 

So I did. And to be honest some people in my life did make some comments on it being strange or narcissistic or laughed as if I was also poking fun of myself in some way.

But I wasn’t. And I’m not. And I hope if you’ve had similar feelings you don’t either. 

Send the card. Share the love. ✨

The polished images and videos I see here are inspiring and motivating, of course. But I have to remember they’re just quite literally a snapshot. 

A lot exists beyond the frames. A lot more than some bloopers like these, of course. And in this season especially, I want to remember that.

✨ THIRTY SEVEN ✨

Marking another year around the sun today. Totally arbitrary in many ways. But also not. 

I love the ritual of it. The built in marker or trip line. Just like the upcoming new year holiday, birthdays give us this great opportunity to take stock. 

And sometimes I think birthdays can be hard — because in our built in reflection point our expectations for what should be don’t line up with what is. And I’d be lying if I said I didn’t experience that too. 

But as I’ve gotten older I really try to frame it differently. Not just positively, because sometimes the feedback I need to give myself isn’t. But without expectations. 

Looking back on where I’ve been and where I’m going with wonder and pride instead of disappointment or a strict plan. An open horizon in front of me. 

And I think it’s going to be a good year. 💜 Thanks for being here with me.

When I was maybe 11 I walked far across town without permission to the grocery store. I’d pooled my change to buy a magazine of Hanson posters. I know what I’m doing, don’t worry, I told my parents when I realized how much trouble I was in. It started before. 

I got my drivers license on my 16th birthday. Drove away from the dmv and then to a town over an hour away without telling anyone. I just wanted to go shopping, I explained to my parents. I wanted to be free. On the road. 

I moved to Louisiana after grad school. I’d wake up early on the weekends to explore the historic neighborhoods. I walked alone in the silent downtown, finding interesting murals and the remnants of wild nights out. I just like to see things, I told my friends.

It started before.

I can be so single focused. Think that what I’m doing is so different from other parts of my life. So new. Oh, I just started solo traveling a few years ago, is my common response. And that’s true — but it started before. The smaller steps. 

The things we are doing now are preparing us for what we’ll do in the future. Small steps are movement. Experience can be transferred. The good or bad — it’s all preparation. We see the individual threads, but not the tapestry that we’re weaving. 

And I can’t wait to see what I’m creating now.

Last night at dinner I was enjoying a meal and wine and a fresh New Yorker at a fancy restaurant and felt very comfortably alone. I noticed a lot of comments from the hostess and wait staff of “just you” but of course I’m used to that.

There was a beautiful older couple next to me but we didn’t interact at all. Until I was leaving and the woman stopped me to say how much she loved my outfit. And in that moment I realized it was the first time that night I felt like anyone noticed I was there at all. And how I was thinking the same about her, but never said. 

I’ve been reading about loneliness a lot lately. A loneliness “epidemic” as many pieces have described it. And I can’t speak for anyone else, of course, but I’ve been trying to really reflect on loneliness in my own life.

After all, I’m alone quite a bit. People ask me about loneliness or my lack of quite a bit. I’ve written many captions circling around all of these same themes.. quite a bit. 

And the truth is, like I’ve said probably ad nauseam here, I’m generally not lonely in the moments I am actually alone. But when it does come up can be around others. 

Loneliness, for me, is a lack of connection or feeling understood. And that involves others. As much as I live my life somewhat pretending I’m a fly on the wall and no one really notices me creepin around — I do feel lonely in those moments when I see a disconnect clearly between myself and others. When I actually feel invisible. 

And I don’t say this to make anyone feel sorry for me, it’s a rare occurrence luckily. But I guess my point to all of this is that I want to use this information about myself to change my behavior towards others.

And that I want to be more like that woman at dinner. I want to say the things I think. Make people feel seen. Connected. And it’s a small step. But we all know where those can lead.

Happy Friday 💜

This past year has been hard for me in a lot of ways. Some that I’ve shared here and many that I haven’t. The phrase “crash and burn” is honestly what I think of most when I try to reflect on year 36.

So going into year 37 I wanted to be very intentional. Start it off with something overtly luxurious and special. I wanted to reset and treat myself.

And this was the perfect place to do it. There’s something so old school and nostalgic about this hotel. I’ve visited several times to stay and often just to walk around when I’m nearby. It sparks joy for me in ways I can explain and many that I can’t. 

So I leaned into it this week. Because if there is one thing I’ve learned through the process of aging it is this: I have to take care of myself. Even in ways that seem kind of indulgent or ridiculous. And I’m so glad I did.

Yesterday I woke up at 4 to a cancelled flight. Rebooked about 4 times before finally getting in the air. Halfway through the flight I hear from my friend and neighbor that we are in a pre-evac area for a wildfire. 

Then on the descent the kid next to me threw up.. everywhere. And then somehow my tripod broke in my luggage. 

I don’t say any of that to complain. Everything worked out and to be honest those are all kind of privileged problems to even have. But I do just want to remind myself and anyone that needs it that: you would never know any of that by looking at this photo at my destination. 

You might even imagine that every moment of my life is just as sweet as this one really was. But life is life for everyone. And as much as I don’t want to be negative — especially about relatively minor inconveniences — I also don’t want to present something false. It’s a fine line. 

I was reading the other day about social media comparison. And how as much as we intellectually know that there’s a lot more behind a frame, it’s hard not to get wrapped up in the story. Like any great book or movie we follow what’s presented to us and make meaning from that. And that’s not wrong, of course. 

It’s just not everything. 

And I need to remember that.

The first day of winter. I wrote this on the first page of my new notebook three years ago on this day. 

A new chapter begins today. The darkest time in the Northern Hemisphere. The beginning of the sun’s life cycle — as it starts growing in strength again.

To know me is to know I love the sun. And as much as I love summer for this reason, I’m learning to appreciate the winter months. Life is made up of extremes. Oscillating between light and dark, peaks and valleys — it’s all important. I wouldn’t feel successful if I’d never failed. Wouldn’t know joy if I’d never felt sorrow. 

There wouldn’t be a shortest day of the year if there wasn’t a longest. Wouldn’t be a sunrise if there wasn’t a sunset. 

These cycles in life and nature are beautiful in their simplicity. They force us to notice. Force us to stop. To rest. Reflect. Do less so we can do more. 

So we can start growing in strength again.

I always spend this week doing a life audit of sorts. A more structured reflection and intention setting process. Get honest with myself about the year before, and try to set myself up for the new year without judgement. 

I’ve been thinking about this audio for a while. And realizing that the thing I want to really focus on this year is personal responsibility. Something that I pride myself on, but needs some nurturing. 

Where I may have been reacting to things in the past I want to be creating them. I want to stop wishing things were different and accept what they are.

2022 has been a year of change. Endings and beginnings and discovery.

✨ 2023 ✨

I love a New Year. The energy surrounding change. Every day is a new day, of course. And in every moment we have the chance to choose differently. But, for me, this day is meaningful. A beginning. 

Each year I decide on a word or theme I want to focus on. In the recent past it’s been focused more on ease or rest. But this year I want to focus on more. I want to focus on movement.

I turned 37 a couple weeks ago. A prime number. And I keep thinking about the significance for me. That no other number can be exactly divided in but one and itself. They’re the building blocks of other numbers. 

And I don’t want to be divided either. I want to build from a place of wholeness and strength. I want to move with purpose. Take a series of coordinated actions. Work towards an objective. 

I want movement. So I’m focusing on it.

We are human beings, not human doings. I hear this phrase a lot. And I’ve been thinking of my own interpretation. 

In a new year, new month, week, day, minute — whenever — I find myself thinking of things I want to do differently. Then always realize that doing things only works for me if it’s in an effort to be something. 

So I am constantly deciding who I want to be. 

I’ve told the story of how I started traveling solo to national parks several times. What I may not have adequately explained is that I didn’t have too much of a pull towards actually doing any of it. 

I just wanted to be a person who did. So I did. 

And in the process became that person. Being through doing. Making decisions over and over and disciplining myself towards what I want to be — not what I want to do. 

I am what I do, so I want to choose wisely. Every day.

I’m spending a lot of intentional time reflecting this time of year. Looking back at some of my favorite moments and trips. Noticing the common threads. The places that have made me feel joy and wonder and curiosity and most like myself. 

Arcosanti is one of those places. I first visited maybe 5 years ago after booking a room there on Airbnb. I had no idea what I was getting into and had never heard anything about this experimental town. To say I was blown away would be an understatement. 

Blending the Italian words “cosa” and “anti” meaning “against things” Arcosanti is an experiment in opposition to consumerism and instead focuses on community, architecture, ecology and sustainability — and it’s gorgeous. Unlike anything I’ve ever seen. The geometry got me first and the views second. The food at the cafe is nourishing and the famed bronze bells meditative. 

I’ve visited a couple times since and it’s one of my favorite places to recommend. Stay the night or tour during the day.

Sometimes I am overwhelmed with the idea that everything I’m doing has already been done. The same photos and words and trips and probably even green boxes in another solo travelers notebook. 

I’m reminded of Cormac McCarthys oft repeated quote that “books are made out of books” — that creativity isn’t so much about creating from scratch but rather connecting the dots. 

And that my frustration in striving for originality is only self-defeating. 

So another thing I’m committed to this year is authenticity over originality. Being who I am and doing the things I want to do. Taking the photos and going to the places that feel right. Even if it’s been done a thousand times before — maybe even by me. 

It may not be new, but it’s real. And that’s more important to me.

The thing about solo travel that I feel like I always have to reiterate is that it’s not necessarily somehow better than being with others. I don’t want to promote lone wolfism or hyper independence or doing things in reaction to negative but natural emotions.

But all that being said, I do believe that there is something about a solo endeavor. A trip or lunch or dinner or experience of any kind really that is important. That isn’t innately better than anything else but is valuable in the future on a level that may be. 

To be able to rely on yourself. Understand your own capability and strengths and wisdom. The kind that don’t necessarily come through unless they’re absolutely needed. 

When you’re all you’ve got you have to rely on her. Trust her. Believe in her. 

And ultimately realize who she’s been all along.

I love winter mornings. Laying in bed after I wake up, I already know if it’s snowed or not. I can hear it. It’s quieter. Even from inside. 

Snow is a sound absorber of course, but it’s more than that. The white blanket is calming. The landscape is simplified. Pristine. There’s a reverence that comes with a morning snow. A tendency to slow down. To appreciate. To listen.

So rarely do we experience this kind of calm. This silence. I think of the kid in class that always has to exclaim, “why is it so quiet?” whenever the noise level drops below the normal hum. They’re genuinely surprised. But where is the whispering, the sound of typing, of writing, of music, of me? 

Hiking up the foothills, all I heard was the sound of snow beneath my feet. I was instantly calmer. My brain relaxed. I can breathe again, I thought. So whether you are waking up to snow today or not, I do have one wish for you: find a few moments of quiet. Some time just to yourself. To listen. There is so much to hear.

I knew I had to quit my job at this time last year. And probably the year before, even. I knew for a long time that what I wanted teaching to be — what it once was for me —  probably wasn’t coming back. And I knew that I couldn’t sustain the weight of it for much longer. 

But I didn’t know what else I could do. Because it wasn’t just a job — it was literally who I was. Who I kind of still am. It’s all encompassing. I think of myself as a teacher. And I get that I still am in other ways yada yada but — it’s different. 

The last several months have been a struggle to redefine my self, honestly. Redefine my identity. Or maybe just to get to a place where I don’t put my identity into anything other than whoever I am showing up as in that moment in time. 

A person first and a worker second. Remind myself that output and productivity and even a noble profession doesn’t make me a better or more worthy person. 

I feel like I write different versions of this same story over and over. Because I do. Here and in my journal and in DMs and conversations with friends.

And I think I’m finally starting to believe it.

January is the perfect time to plan some summer national park trips — and I hope New River Gorge is on a lot of your lists. The newest officially designed “National Park” in the system — it is incredible. 

I’ve visited twice and am hoping to get out on the country roads of West Virginia again very soon. 

On my first visit I was incredibly lucky to stay on a private island on the New River @guesthousewv The Cabin on Coney Island was truly one of the most amazing travel experiences I’ve ever had. Or experiences period. 

From the second a local outfitter took me out on the water to the island I couldn’t contain my excitement. My gratitude. To have this little slice of paradise all to myself if just for a night. I made a fire and grilled some dinner. Watched the sunset and laid on the beach. Feeling so far away while still being so close. 

Truly bucket list. Have you stayed on a private island? Visited New River Gorge? West Virginia?

Happy Saturday 💜 

This is the vibe I am cultivating this weekend. And let’s be honest, all the time 😂 

Protecting my peace. Setting boundaries and doing my best to keep them. Putting myself into the situations that advance my goals and desires. And staying out of the ones that don’t. 🤗

What are you up to this weekend? 

@maisontetonia

We see a lot of the same places on social media. I do, anyways. And for good reason, of course. The iconic spots in the west are iconic for a reason. 

But after visiting all 50 states solo I am more sure than ever that there is beauty and awe inspiring nature everywhere. And some of the best might be where you least expect it. 

A lot of these states are known for their beauty of course. But what surprised me was how vast the landscapes were. How varied. The lack of crowds and abundance of outdoor opportunities. The lack of traffic jams on the way to a trailhead 😂 The places I’ve yet to see on my Instagram feed.

So maybe surprising isn’t actually the right word. Underrated, maybe. 

Hidden gems that aren’t hidden at all. 

What’s been a place that’s surprised you?

How strange it is to be perceived. I’ve been thinking about that lately. Because despite how much I share online, I don’t really like to consider the possible ways my words or photos are being interpreted. How I am possibly seen by others. 

Many times I just kind of… share. Hope for the best. For the right person to connect at the right time. If I think too much about how thousands of mostly strangers are regarding me I think I might lose it. 

Because acknowledging perception leads to acknowledgment of judgment. And while I know we all do it it still feels uncomfortable to not be in control. 

So I remind myself that I started sharing here for precisely that reason. So many years ago (that feels very dramatic but it has been a long time 😂) Because I have a very strong desire for control. For certainty. For assurance. 

But in order to be vulnerable and share I have to let go of that. And it can still be really hard even after all this time. 

I always think of this quote from @glennondoyle when she was being interviewed by @oprah several years ago. She says that 

“telling your truth clears the field for others to tell theirs.” 

And since I’m more comfortable leading than being vulnerable that framing really works for me. 

So I keep trying to clear the field. Share my story. Every day.

Enjoying some time at home 💜🐈‍⬛ 

I deliberately didn’t plan any travel this month — for the first month probably in years. And to be honest it was difficult at first. To go through my daily routines without the excitement of an upcoming trip. 

So I spent a lot of time thinking about how an ideal day would look like at home. The things I’d do and what I would create. The things that bring me joy. And cooking was at the top of the list. #greenchefpartner #ad 

I’ve always enjoyed cooking, but it can be tough to sustain as one person who travels consistently. The act of creation is of course a core value for me, and the mindfulness that following a process brings is really gratifying for me. 

That’s why I’m always happy to receive my @greenchef boxes. I’ve been using Green Chef for several years — I love the vegetable forward chef-created dishes that I can easily recreate on any night in. The easy to follow recipes are delicious and elevated, while saving me time at the grocery store. 

And as the first organic certified meal kit company — and only meal kit that is both plastic and carbon offset — Green Chef actually creates less food waste than retail grocery stores. 

Want to try for yourself? Use my code EMILYVENTURES60 to get 60% off + free shipping! Click the link in my bio for more details ✨👩🏻‍🍳

It’s that time again 🤗 

If you’re planning summer trips to one of these National Parks, you’ll need reservations — and most will be available soon/already are and will be gone almost immediately. 

While the system can be confusing and I miss the days of just winging it, the reservation systems are necessary in some places to prevent overcrowding and damage to the environment. 

Are you planning any trips to these parks this summer? Others? What do you think of reservation and timed entry systems?

Focusing on the process. Trusting the process. The day in and day out. Inspiration, to me, comes from action. So if Im waiting for it to strike Im going to be waiting a long time. 

Because life isn’t about where I are or what Ive already mastered. It’s about where Im going. The journey itself. 

So I’m trusting it to lead me. Learning along the way.

I travel solo about 98% of the time. I’ve visited all 50 states and 58/63 major National Parks completely alone in my 30s. And I get a lot of questions, as you might imagine. Like “but who is taking your photos?” About 35 times a day 😂

So here are some answers :) And some of my solo traveler must haves. 

Have you traveled solo? What are your must haves?

Happy National Plan for Vacation Day! I read online that it was anyways 😂🤷🏻‍♀️

It’s funny I was just thinking this morning about the first real solo trip that I planned for myself purely for pleasure. Nearly 8 years ago. I decided around this time of year that I would go to the Grand Canyon for spring break. I needed a purpose. I was teaching and felt like it was my entire life. My whole identity. 

I felt that way because it was the truth. 

So I wanted to do something different. I’ve told the story of my great uncle (also a math teacher) inspiring me to travel to the Grand Canyon like he did. But I don’t share as much about the first leg of the trip. 

I drove down south from Denver to Taos. Honestly I only knew it was a town because I remember reading that Julia Robert’s lived there 😂 I spent a night in Taos and continued on to Santa Fe. Stayed in an Airbnb for the first time alone. 

I wasn’t too sure what to do with myself. I went to Trader Joes and bought myself wine and dinner. Browsed some local shops and bought myself a card with this long quote (scroll for the whole thing) 

The second line said “if you don’t like something, change it”

And I realized in that moment that’s exactly what I was doing. 

And I was really proud of myself. 

(A more recent photo from New Mexico and some photos from that first trip ✨)

What I wrote when I first entered Monument Valley: “I saw the sandstone buttes come into view and gasped. The West will do that to you. I’ve criss-crossed back and forth through the southwest countless times and I’m still in awe. Still surprised. 

I drove down into the valley and immediately choked up. There are a few places I travel that always bring me to tears. This one is firmly on that list. Of places that are completely overwhelming. Awe inspiring. Sacred.”

There’s a similar story for all of these places. And more, of course. But these will always stuck out. Places that truly changed me. 

What places are like that for you?

Don’t read the comments. We’ve all heard it. But one of the best things about Instagram is the connection — through comments. But I have to be honest, the negative comments after all these years still bother me. And I used to I wish it wasn’t true — that I could brush them off easily — but I can’t. And I’m not sure that’s something I want. Because to create I need to be connected. To others and myself. And brushing off my feelings isn’t going to help.

What I want is to be able to create without fear — put my work and words out then let them go. I can’t be attached to the outcomes. I can do my best to speak from love, but I can’t control others interpretations of it. Others life experience may lead them to find something outside of my intended meaning. And that’s okay. It’s their experience. 

Because the gap between what I mean and what is read is in flux. There are always prefaces and post-scripts and clarifications that could be added. But if that’s my concern, then I wouldn’t share at all. Which leads to connection. It’s circular. Take the good with the bad, right? 

I’m working on it. Thanks for giving me grace.

Dreams do come true ✨

I was born in a town known for the railroad. We had a Railroad Days festival in the summer, the National Railroad Hall of Fame and the one thing everyone learned in drivers ed was how to get around up or under all the main railroad crossings in town. 

I remember the first time I rode the Amtrak to Chicago on my own. I was enamored. I wanted to exclusively ride the rails from then on. It was raining outside and this perfect moment I had romanticized growing up. 

So when I had the chance to spend a day on Napa Valley @winetrain I couldn’t board quick enough. 

From breakfast and bubbles to lunch and tastings and wineries stops — it was one of the best days I’ve had in a long time. Such a unique way to see the Napa valley and treat yourself.

Good morning from @fairmontsonoma ✨The perfect place to slow down and relax. 

I was texting with a friend the other day and they asked how it feels not to be in a classroom this year. And my first reaction was to tell them that it’s been good but that I need to start hustling more. Be more productive. You know the productivity shame spiral. 

And their response — as probably my most productive friend — was really comforting and honestly freeing to me. 

“Part of the process is slowing down.” She said. “You’ll be ready to get into gear at just the right moment” 

And I have felt that way too, of course. I’ve probably talked about it a lot here. But it felt like maybe I was just being too easy on myself. Sometimes you just need to hear things from someone else’s perspective. Someone you trust. 

Remember again that trusting the process includes slowing down. Go slow to go fast like I always used to tell my students. 

And now, here, I’m taking that advice seriously.

Quick detour 😍

You didn’t think I could visit California without visiting Yosemite did you? Of course not :)

I could only manage to get to the park on a weekend during firefall (again 😂) and had to do some work arounds to get in without an advance reservation (more on that later) but once I was it was all worth it. 

It was raining and cold all day, with very few people and lots of solitude. At first I was disappointed that the clouds rolled in right before I could get out and explore. That some parts of the park I love so much were completely obscured. Then I realized how lucky I was. 

Not just to know what was behind those clouds, but for the opportunity to see them differently. Appreciate new parts I never noticed before. New contrasts with the snow. Without the normal crowds. Not even distracted with many photos because my hands were too cold to set up the tripod 😂

Reminding myself that I can go to the same places and experience them completely differently. And how remarkable is that?

People always ask me for recommendations on less popular trails in National Parks. And I get it, of course. It feels great to be hiking in solitude on a trail that still feels like a secret.

But that being said, I always recommend hitting some of the more popular trails as well. Because y’all, they’re popular for a reason. And they def live up to the hype.

Whenever I post a photo at a place like this I get a lot of comments or messages about a better, more secretive place I should go instead. There’s this underlying idea that if a lot of people like something it can’t be as special as we think. That the reason for the crowds is the crowds themselves. 

Not true here. At all. Yosemite Valley is one of the most breathtaking places I have ever seen. The first time I visited I was sick. So so so sick. I was staying in a vintage trailer outside the park and it took everything in my achy body to get up before sunrise to head into the park. I was nearly crying I was in so much pain. The kind of moment when traveling alone really stinks. 

And then I saw these landscapes. I forgot about how I felt because a whole new range of feelings hit me. Awe. Wonder. Appreciation. Insignificance.

I’ve been back several times, and I still love going to the crowded touristy spots. Laying by the river or sitting in the village with a beer. I spent an hour once listening in to a mother and brother excitedly waiting for their brother to get back to meet them. He was planning on proposing on a hike, and the family was surprising them after. 

On this trip I inadvertently got in the middle of a very beautiful proposal. Those are the kind of moments that make traveling alone really great. 

Its so special to have this amazing life changing experience at the same time as others. Even if we never say a word. We shared this moment. And it was beautiful.

Years ago when I started posting more on Instagram it was an attempt to be more present — not less. To seek out beauty and notice the things I may not have before.

✨ 59/63 ✨National Park of American Samoa

To be honest this park was the most intimidating when I originally decided to visit all major parks solo. 

And after being here a few days I still can’t believe it’s real. 

I’ll have a lot more to say in the next few days. But for now, I’m just feeling proud.

I’m making it. 

😍🤗💜

The @nationalparkservice just released 2022 visitation statistics and National Park of American Samoa grabbed the title of least visited National Park. After my solo visit this week I am not surprised in the least 😂

With just two flights to the island per week it was easy to spot the just 2 other visitors and 1 family visiting the park. With just 1,887 visitors in all of last year, the chances of having a trail to yourself aren’t just likely — it’s virtually guaranteed. 

Located 5,000 miles from the mainland and south of the equator, it’s a national park that still feels like a secret. American Samoans are incredibly warm and friendly and kind. I could not have asked for a better experience on their island. 

Also Interestingly and importantly — the NPS only leases the land from American Samoans who retain land ownership of the park and the island. 

Is it on your travel list? What do you want to know about the trip? The island?

Made it to the beach 🌴🏖️

Later than you might imagine, being on an island and all. But, like I’ve talked about here, American Samoa is unique in its land ownership. Nearly all the land and beach is family/communally owned. There are limited beaches one can visit — after asking permission from the owners and generally paying a small fee. 

I read about a beachfront bar that came with amazing reviews — but most from before the islands long shutdown. I emailed the owner, Tisa, and she immediately responded that they would host a traditional Samoan umu feast the next night. 

I of course reserved my spot and she encouraged me to invite other travelers since they’ve just started opening back up. So I went down to the hotel bar and invited everyone there 😂

Tisa graciously said I could come early to her paradise and enjoy the beach — and oh my goodness did I. Swimming all alone in the most beautiful water surrounded by incredible lush hills and clear skies. It was as close to a dream I’ve ever experienced while awake. 

The dinner was scheduled for some researchers coming over from another island, who ended up delayed and couldn’t make it. But four other people I met at the hotel bar did :) 

We watched the preparation of our amazing meal in the traditional umu — an above ground oven with food cooked on hot rocks. Listened to Tisa tell us about her life, her land and the island. Enjoyed an absolute feast together watching the sunset (with incredible pina coladas) and shared travel stories in between exclamations of “this is the best meal I’ve ever had” and “I’m so glad I ended up here tonight”

Still feels like a dream looking back at these photos. And I’m so glad I ended up there on this night. 

*These are all at Tisas Barefoot Bar. A must on the island.

Happy Friday 🌴🏖️

I spent hours here one afternoon in American Samoa. Listening to the waves. Feeling the sun. Reading. Closing my eyes. An attempt at mindfulness but also, I was tired 😂

It’s taken me a long time to give myself permission to really relax on big trips. I write about it a lot because I need to continue to convince myself, honestly. 

I think back to when I first started this quest and I truly can’t believe how much I would fit in to a weekend before going back to teaching a bunch of middle schoolers math all week. Just to do it again. 

I’m sure some of it was just being younger but I think there was also just a feeling of missing out. I started solo traveling in part so that I wouldn’t have to feel left out like I sometimes would as a kid, teenager and into young adulthood. I wanted to be able to chart my own course and do it all regardless of anyone’s invite. 

And I’ve done that, for sure. But it can be difficult for me to remember that doing it all doesn’t have to mean actually doing “it all” or for all of the time. That rest is important and spending time on a trip without seeing something new or creating any kind of new content is just as valuable. 

And it really was. 

What are you up to this weekend? What kind of traveler are you? Constantly going or do you take time to rest?

I got back from my trip and almost immediately picked up a job subbing middle school math classes. On a Friday afternoon 😳 

You’d think my 13 years of full-time middle school math teaching would have been a warning, but I’ve been in the midst of.. an investigation of sorts. I’ve subbed in a few schools of different grade levels and subjects in a different district to see if there is something there. To try to better place my feelings about teaching or not teaching. See if it’s just me, the school, the grade, whatever. And of course I also always need extra money 😂🤷🏻‍♀️

So anyways, I’ve kind of been avoiding the middle school math because that’s all I’ve really ever done. It’s what I know. It’s what took an incredible amount of courage and bravery to step away from. It’s not really part of my self made completely unscientific experiment. 

But I decided to see what would happen. And to be honest, it was great. (Not the English class I also had to cover — def do not recommend 😂) But the math classes, they were great. 

And it has made me so so angry. That this thing I love and I without question am an expert in is not something I can realistically do. That all the “other” has still made teaching a totally unsustainable and unattractive/unaffordable career. 

I feel my most confident teaching a 12 year old kid how to solve for x. Really. And I’m so angry that I can’t do it without extreme burnout and stress and gaslighting and all of the negative things I’m sure you’ve heard from the educator in your life. 

Why I’m sharing all this with 69 thousand people I’m not really sure. I don’t have any answers, obviously. 

But all I’m really concerned about is asking the right questions. And I am very much doing that.

I got dressed up to take myself to dinner my last night in Oahu. But first took a walk on the beach after sunset to look at the moon. Watched the clouds turn from orange to grey. 

I walked in between the families taking photos and friends posing in the surf to get a different vantage point. There it was. So big it almost felt like I could reach out and touch it if I walked long enough. 

I’m here and I’m experiencing that I am here. I say that to myself a lot. 

I remember so vividly the moment in this photo. The young girl who offered to take a photo after seeing me struggle to selfie 😂Then spending my time just staring. Trying to take it all in.

Breathing the air. The peace of the water amongst so many people. 

Everything else washed away. I am so overwhelmed in this moment. So grateful. So happy. 

I’m here and I’m experiencing that I am here.

Someone asked me today about “my career goals” or plan for my life. And I answered honestly that… I don’t really know. I’m exploring, I said. Figuring out what to keep and what to leave behind. What new to bring into my life going forward. 

But one thing I know for sure, I said, is that I like working with people. I like being in a classroom. I loved working at a grocery store in high school and college. I like to interact. 

And I understand that may be surprising based on, like, everything you see here 😂

But it reminded me of an interaction Ive written about before. On my last trip in 2020 before everything shut down. 

When I was traveling alone as usual and stopped at a hole in the wall place near the SC beach. I sat at the bar, ordered a local beer and way too much food for one person. Picked up my book and started to read, as I always do. A much older woman came to the bar and sat next to me. She was dressed far too nicely for this place, and immediately ordered a huge fried dinner and just a water. 

And we talked, as we always do. Got to know one another. She offered me a french fry before she started eating and I offered her a hush puppy before I did. And immediately after she left it happened again. A much older man and the same situation. We talked. We learned about each other. He recommended the best museums in the area and told me about his family ski trip. Gave me his card. 

These were small interactions. You could argue they weren’t too deep. But I think about them all the time. And hundreds of moments like them. The kindness, the shared moments in time. We’ll likely never be together again. 

Reminding myself that I travel solo in large part to connect with others. To set myself up for these moments. To be available to them.

Do you travel solo? Do you enjoy meeting others when you do?

It’s easier when I find a motivation, a friend said before a long training ride. And what is it today? I asked. Well, today it’s just something I have to do, they replied.

I’ve been thinking about this a lot. The stuff I just have to do to reach a larger goal. Continuing on when things aren’t as easy as I want them to be. When I can’t find my motivation. When the journey becomes a slog. Which has been happening more often that I’d like lately. 

I like to think I’m a process person. That I’m more concerned with the journey than the destination. And I usually truly am. But what happens when the journey becomes difficult? When I lose my motivation? When I’m inclined to turn back around or forgo the intended outcome entirely? Take the easy way out? Its not all about the end. I can find learning in the pursuit, I think. And I can. But I miss out on a lot of finishes that way. 

Because the truth is I’m often afraid to see things through because I’m afraid to fail. 
Afraid the destination might be underwhelming. That the finish line might not be as exciting as I’d hoped. The trail might be more interesting than the mountain top. 

I don’t want to be afraid anymore. I want to keep going. Do the things I just have to do. Be consistent when I’m not motivated. To finish the things that are important to me. I want to learn from the journey AND the destination.

Gradually, then suddenly. Day turns to night. Winter to spring.

Good or bad. It starts small. Maybe even unnoticed at all. Our efforts (or lack of) compounding out of sight. 

Change is happening all the time. Slowly slowly slowly then all of a sudden you’ve changed. 

The dark season that felt like it would never end suddenly turned into light. The snow is melting and the trees will bud. You’re finally on the summit. At the edge. Doing the thing you once dreamed of.

And ask yourself, how did I get here?

Gradually, then suddenly. 

Happy spring 🌸

Just a reminder: it’s not only valid if it’s more. More miles. More sweat. More effort. That more is somehow better. That only something in excess is productive and worthy of admiration. I just don’t think that’s true. 

There always seems to be someone who is telling me I’m doing it wrong. That I don’t look like I’ve “put in any miles” in my photos. That a beautiful view is “just the parking lot” as if that’s some kind of own. That I can’t wear a bathing suit online as a woman who wants to be taken seriously. I can’t hike or camp or travel solo and be safe. I didn’t visit the right trail or go far enough into the backcountry. That I need someone else to protect me. To tell me what to do. 

Luckily I’ve never bought in to that. Ever 😂 

Tons of beauty can be found right from the road. The parking lot. It’s all around. More isn’t always more. 

Sometimes ease is just what I need. And there’s so much beauty to be found in it.

It’s been a weird day. For lots of reasons. But I keep coming back to this thought. 

I always tell myself that I don’t know what the next wave will be like — just that it’s coming.

And that I have the power to remain steadfast regardless of what’s around me. Tranquil in a storm. Not denying reality, just moving with it as gracefully as I can. 

At peace.

Dreaming of American Samoa 🌴

I like talking big dreams, a friend said the other day. What’s one of yours, Emily? They asked.

I paused for a moment. Knowing the answer, but wondering if it was “big” enough. Feeling the familiar twinge of imposter syndrome. 

Well to be honest, I replied, it’s what I’m doing right now — I’m not thinking too far beyond that.

When I was teaching I would write a “Daily Celebration” on the board every day. One of these random (kind of made up?) days. At first I just wrote it on the board but didn’t point it out, wondering if kids would notice. If they would think it was cheesy.

But it never took long. What’s the day today? They’d ask. Some kids would come in early before class to help me look it up and argue over who could write it on the white board. We’d research the ones we were unsure of or talk about our connections to it. They never had anything to do with math class — except maybe Ada Lovelaces birthday or pi day — but they had everything to do with creating the culture of our classroom. 

And something that started as something maybe “made up” became real. A real part of our day and our class and our culture. 

And it was a small thing. But I like to celebrate the small stuff.

I’ve always been something of an “input” person. Im curious. I want to know things. When I was young I read that Warren Buffet spends 6 hours a day reading and immediately decided I should probably do that too 😂

I take a lot in. Consume. Books and news and essays and podcasts and tv shows and and and. And travel, to me, is the greatest input. 

Seeing new places and experiencing new things. Driving on new roads and meeting new people. It’s what I love.

In my math classes we would learn about input/output tables. In goes one number and out comes another. What happens in between? What operation, or rule? 

I think of myself and my tendency for input. But what happens next? In between? How can I create instead of getting lost in constant consumption. Not give up one for the other. 

So I’m trying to focus more on the output. I want to create.

I started putting patches on this pack to start conversation. I travel alone, and am not naturally great at organically meeting others, so this seemed like a good way. And it has been! People always ask me about a place they see I’ve been. For recommendations or to reminisce together. It’s great. 

But for some reason I still find myself sort of hiding it. I set it down facing backwards. Pack it in my luggage. I’m not sure why that is. Why I feel like an imposter. Like if someone sees my pack and then has a conversation with me it will be underwhelming. 

That these patches might signify to them that I’m cooler than I actually am 😂 Or on the flip side they’ll think I’m trying to be something I’m not. 

It’s funny, for someone who shares a lot on the internet, I don’t actually like to share. I have to push myself to do it. One of the reasons I like solo travel is the ability to move through places unnoticed. Be a fly on the wall. I don’t want to stand out. And I think sometimes that’s okay. 

But through solo travel I’ve also learned that it’s okay to be seen. To feel proud of my accomplishments (and patches). To literally wear them with pride. That it doesn’t matter what it symbolizes to someone else. Or what they think that says about me. 

What matters is what I say about me.

It’s nearly the end of the school year. Im feeling mixed emotions about it. I taught math for 13 years. At 6 different schools. From 6-12th grades. In 2 different states. 

I wrote this maybe 5 years ago on this day, and I can’t help but look back on it to reflect. After leaving last year, I still feel so many of these things. Still feel sort of stuck. Like a quitter. I mean, I am 😂 but I needed to hear this. 
————- 
Teachers who leave, or who are feeling stuck, often have this huge identity crisis. Teaching is one of those professions that supersedes anything else about you. You don’t see “Colorado woman _____” on the news, you see “Colorado teacher _____” It’s a strong identity. It says something about you. Your character. 

But that also brings a lot of pressure. I feel it. I’m not leaving now, but I’ve thought about it. I’ve been burnt out. Felt unappreciated. And I think about what would happen If I did. I wouldn’t be ______, _____, or _______. How would I have influence? Would I lose respect? It’s a lot.

And it keeps people stuck. But you know what, as much as I respect and love fellow teachers, I’ve realized we are all teachers. We all have an opportunity to influence the world. The next generation. We can all use our time and effort to make things better. 

We teach through our actions. We teach others how to treat us. How to treat the earth. How to show love, compassion, and friendship. We are modeling everyday and everywhere that we go. 

So while you celebrate the teachers in your life remember that we aren’t the only ones teaching. We are all in this together. Help us teach humanity.

“You’re fearless” people sometimes say to me. Or some version of, “You’re braver than I am”. And I have to laugh. My immediate response is always disbelief. No way, I’m scared all the time, I think. 

Remembering the times I’ve had to work so hard to talk myself into doing things others – seemingly – don’t think twice about. The times I have felt so frail and weak and terrified. 

Then I remember when I wasn’t. The times I’ve been brave—the evidence I have on that side. The side that others see. 

And it helps me the next time. When I need it. To see myself through the eyes of someone else. Someone who doesn’t see the moments (many moments) of fear and worry. 

They only see one side and I tend to only see the other. 

But I need to remember that they’re both me.

I have to be honest, even though I do things like this all the time, I still had those moments whenever I saw other people in the distance that I should somehow be ashamed. For taking photos. That they would think I was just doing it “for the gram”.

Then I quickly let the thought go, because dang I was having a great time sitting here watching the clouds, feeling the sun, and eating a sandwich 😂.

But it’s something I think about frequently, actually. When I plan specific outfits around an activity or always buy flowers for my hotels and airbnbs. When I’m curling my hair or putting on makeup. Am I doing this for me or for the photo?

And to be honest, I think it’s both — and I think that’s really more than okay. For me anyways. Because when I do it for a photo I do it for me. 

You see, when I started going out alone I really had no purpose. No direction or goal. And I enjoyed it, but I needed a focus.

So I started taking photos. And I started seeing things differently. When I’m mentally in a bad place, getting ready and going outside to take some photos helps. Buying flowers might be a nice prop, but they also make me happy. Really really happy. 

I’m always surrounded by beauty — because I look for it. And I create it. And the why in this case, for me, really isn’t as important as the result.

My grandma made me this blanket. Just a blanket of scraps and leftovers, she said. I kept it in my car for years. Snuggled up with it at campsites. After she passed away a couple years ago I brought it into my apartment. I put it in a basket and tried not to think about it too much. 

When I was maybe 10 she gave me a shirt she had made for me. It was white and red and green. “I didn’t know it was Christmas” a kid said to me in school. I sent them daggers through my eyes for days. Weeks maybe. I was quiet and obstinate. Refused to speak to them or any other kid. My teacher. They’d put a worksheet on my desk and I would just stare at it or throw it off my desk. 

I somehow ended up quitting school that year actually. Just in 5th grade. To be homeschooled. But really I was just mad. Not really at the kid, but at the idea of being contained. It felt like a prison. Like I was becoming domesticated in the midst of a bunch of rude 10 year olds. 

And looking back and reading that paragraph sounds like a joke but it wasn’t. At all. 

I guess it’s ironic that I later became a teacher. Willingly put myself back in the environment that I once hated so much. For so many years. But I loved it for a really really long time. 

Until I didn’t. 

It’s been a year since I’ve been in a classroom full time. And when I think about it it feels unbelievable but also completely right. 

And I’m feeling like I can maybe, finally, move past that season. I don’t feel contained anymore. 

My grandma always told me to keep doing what I wanted to do. Not to listen to other peoples opinions of it. She was proud of whatever I chose. 

And I think I’m finally starting to be too.

When I’m alone I’m not lonely. I might have seen it that way in the past. May have miscoded in my mind my physical state as an emotional one. But all the cliches are true: if you are comfortable with yourself, if you like yourself, if you treat yourself with the care of a friend

I can only speak for myself. I can only maybe possibly ever resonate with anyone beyond myself by just being myself. Sharing my own thoughts and truths and wondering and ramblings.

I took a short flight this morning (not on a helicopter unfortunately 😂). To an airport I’ve been to before, to travel to a place I haven’t. I’ll tell you when I leave, of course. But it reminded me how interesting it is — to fly.

I went through a period of extreme flight phobia not that long ago. I was nervous at every bump. Took medication before each flight. Looked up the statistics on how likely we were to go down. 

But I could try to learn everything about the physics of flying and it made no difference— I still couldn’t trust it. I wasn’t in control. And even something statistically unlikely still has that one in a whatever chance. And what if I was that one, I’d think.

And then one day I got on a plane and I just…. didn’t care. Wasn’t nervous. Didn’t react the way I had over and over for years. And I didn’t do anything differently. I had long ago accepted my fate and was just determined to do it anyway. 

But somewhere along the line something shifted. And I’m constantly trying to pinpoint what. I started trusting more? Exposure therapy? I’d just done it enough not to care? 

I still don’t know. But it makes me hopeful. That even the things we think will always be with us can just fall away. That it’s not always due to an outsized effort. 

Or maybe it is, we’ve just changed enough not to notice. I accepted my fate and was determined to do it anyway. And in doing so found sometimes I dont have to try so hard after all.

I’m ashamed that I felt that way for so long. Because the truth is it was never that there wasn’t anything to do — I just wasn’t a person who did things. 

I’m reminded of that every time I am back in the heartland. Reminded very clearly during this trip.

I exist. I’m here. I think in some ways I started solo traveling because I felt like I didn’t. Or maybe because I didn’t want to — be seen, that is. 

I tried to forget that I existed outside of my own little world. And to be honest it’s always been very easy for me to focus on what I’m seeing and not who is seeing me. 

I’m still surprised when someone starts talking to me or tells me they like my jacket, or sunglasses. Oh, you see me. Weird. And comforting. But also sometimes destabilizing, if I’m honest. To be reminded that this all goes both ways. 

I post online and often immediately after think, oh wow, people can see this 😂 and read it. A lot of people, even. And have opinions on it. 

I’d love to say I never care what others think of me, and in most situations I don’t. But seeing myself through the eyes of others is still something I’m getting used to, even now.

But more than anything I’m glad to be seen by you all. I’m grateful for it. And I am learning from it. 

Thank you.

“She finally found her happiness”

I heard someone say this the other day in relation to a public figure getting engaged. And I immediately wanted to respond, but held back 😂

To say that while yes, I’m happy when people are happy. And find themselves in situations that make them happy. With people who contribute to their happiness — or even make them happier than they were before. 

But the idea of ultimately “finding happiness” in another person has always been something that doesn’t make sense to me. That actually makes me feel sad for the people who speak that way, if that’s actually how they feel. It might just be semantics, I know.

But that’s never been a goal in my life. I’m not trying to “find” anything. Especially not in anyone else. Because it’s all already there. It’s within me. It is me. In my life. And relationships with others of course is a part of a life well-lived, but I come into my relationships with others already whole. I don’t need that from them. 

I just want to be happy with myself. The way I live my life. And the rest will — and does — flow from there.
